    "The philosopher who formulated the \"hard problem of consciousness\" is **David Chalmers**[1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LW59lMvxmY4), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Chalmers).\n\nHe coined the term in the mid-1990s (formally presenting it in a 1995 article and his 1996 book, *The Conscious Mind*) to describe the challenge of explaining why and how physical processes in the brain give rise to subjective, first-person experience[3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHTiQrrUhUA), [4](https://www.reddit.com/r/askphilosophy/comments/1nacbwl/by_which_philosopher_when_did_the_hard_problem_of/), [2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Chalmers), [5](https://medium.com/@matherscd/david-chalmers-and-the-hard-problem-of-consciousness-0909ef73a744).\n\n### Key Context:\n*   **The \"Hard\" vs. \"Easy\" Problems:** Chalmers distinguishes his \"hard\" problem from what he calls the \"easy\" problems of consciousness[3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHTiQrrUhUA), [6](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OsYUWtLQBS0). The latter involve explaining functions such as the ability to discriminate stimuli, integrate information, or report mental states\u2014processes that are, in principle, explainable through neurobiology and computational models.\n[3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHTiQrrUhUA), [6](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OsYUWtLQBS0)*   **The Core Question:** The \"hard\" problem asks why these physical processes are accompanied by an inner life. [1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LW59lMvxmY4), [3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHTiQrrUhUA)Even if we knew everything about how the brain processes information, the question of *why* it feels like something to be us\u2014why there is a subjective \"what it is like\" quality to experience\u2014remains unanswered.\n*   [1](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LW59lMvxmY4), [5](https://medium.com/@matherscd/david-chalmers-and-the-hard-problem-of-consciousness-0909ef73a744)**The Meta-Problem:** In more recent years, Chalmers has also introduced the \"meta-problem of consciousness,\" which seeks to explain why we find the hard problem so puzzling in the first place, and why we are inclined to talk about it as a profound mystery.[3](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yHTiQrrUhUA), [6](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OsYUWtLQBS0)"
